      answer:
        '**Greedy decoding is deterministic in math; the infrastructure underneath isn\'t.** Argmax of logits is a deterministic operation, but on a hosted API none of the supporting layers are.\n\nWhat actually breaks the guarantee:\n\n- **Continuous batching** — your request joins a batch with different other requests each call; batched matmul produces slightly different floats because fp arithmetic isn\'t associative.\n- **Multi-GPU reduction order** — tensor-parallel forward passes reduce across GPUs in non-fixed order.\n- **Mixed precision rounding** — fp16/bf16 ops round differently depending on intermediate state.\n- **MoE routing** — top-k expert selection on borderline tokens can flip with tiny logit perturbations, and one flipped token cascades.\n\nOn a borderline token where two candidates have nearly equal logits, last-bit fp differences flip the tiebreaker. OpenAI\'s `seed` is "best effort" — closer to reproducible but not guaranteed. Anthropic doesn\'t expose a seed because the guarantee they could give is too weak to be useful.\n\nSelf-hosted vLLM, batch size 1, single GPU, greedy, fixed seed — *that* is actually deterministic. Turn on batching or tensor parallelism and it\'s gone.\n\n**Never write a test that asserts an exact LLM string.** Test structural properties (valid JSON, key present, length in range), or LLM-as-judge, or both. And `temperature=0.7` is the wrong default for anything non-creative — JSON validity drops from ~99.5% at T=0 to ~95% at T=0.7 to <90% at T=1.0. Every retry costs money.',
