      answer:
        '**A weekend of XGBoost on the same labels hits 96% at <$0.0001/call and 3ms p95.** This is the modal story of 2025-2026: for tabular classification and regression, **gradient-boosted trees beat LLMs on cost, latency, and usually accuracy**. The 1000× cost ratio is real and compounds on every product decision.\n\nWhy boosted trees win on tabular data:\n\n- Handle mixed types natively (numeric, categorical, missing). No encoding ceremony.\n- No feature scaling required — splits are scale-invariant.\n- Capture non-linear interactions automatically — depth-6 tree can express "if income>80K AND region=NYC AND age<30".\n- Train in minutes on a laptop. Serve in microseconds. Few-MB artifact.\n- Feature importance + SHAP for free. Try getting that from an LLM.\n\nThe rule: **if the input is a structured row, the answer is classical ML.** Default to LightGBM; fall back to XGBoost if it overfits; fall back to CatBoost if you have brutal high-cardinality categoricals.\n\nLLMs win on **ambiguous text and generative output** — semi-structured customer complaints into 12 buckets with explanation, zero-shot classification when you have <100 labels, one-shot internal tools. Above ~1000 labeled examples on a tabular schema, the classical model wins. "We tried fine-tuning, it\'s still 87%" is almost always "wrong tool entirely — try gradient boosting before fine-tuning anything."',
